[[File:Tulta2.jpg|thumb|alt=Toppled Powerline Tower alt text|"Bolt Weevils" tore down 14 powerline towers in Minnesota in the late 1970s.]]

The '''CU Project Controversy''' involved years of protest against a proposed [[high-voltage direct current]] [[Electric power transmission|powerline]] that was erected on the property of hundreds of farmers in west central [[Minnesota]] in the late 1970s. Opposition to the powerline began in 1974 and involved political parties, churches, civic organizations, and businesses in several different Minnesota counties.<ref name=oralhistory>{{cite journal |last1=Fogerty |first1=James E. |year=1985 |title=Oral History and Environmental Controversy: The Minnesota Powerline Project |journal=The Oral History Review |volume=13 |pages=81}}</ref><ref name="wellstone13">{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=13}}</ref> The powerline was reviewed in 33 meetings in [[North Dakota]] and 48 meetings in Minnesota and in two years of hearings; at the time, no other powerline in Minnesota state history had gone through such a drawn-out review process.<ref name="fogerty80"/><ref name=Minnesota1>{{cite web |url=http://news.minnesota.publicradio.org/features/200212/09_losurem_powerline4/ |title='Rudy's Raiders' go home |first=Mary |last=Losure |author= |authorlink= |coauthors= |date= |work= |publisher=Minnesota Public Radio |location= |page= |pages= |language= |trans_title= |format= |doi= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |accessdate=November 23, 2009 |quote= |ref= |separator= |postscript= }}</ref> Multiple candidates for state office included the powerline issue as part of their platforms.<ref name=oralhistory /> Farmers employed tractors, manure spreaders, and ammonia sprayers and used [[direct action]] and [[civil disobedience]] in an attempt to prevent construction of the line. Powerline protests drew national attention when over 200 state troopers, nearly half the [[Minnesota State Patrol|Minnesota Highway Patrol]], were deployed to ensure that construction of the line would continue.<ref name=Wellstone1>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=4}}</ref> During a two year period, a group of opponents to the line who called themselves "bolt weevils" tore down 14 powerline towers and shot out nearly 10,000 electrical insulators.<ref name=wellstonen>{{cite journal |last1=Wellstone |first1=Paul David |last2=Casper |first2=Barry M. |date=26 December 1981|title=The Rural Energy War: Report from the Front Lines |journal=The Nation |volume= |issue= |pages=699 |url= |doi= }}</ref>

==Background==
===The growth of electrical co-ops===
The CU Powerline Project was initiated by [[Great River Energy|Cooperative Power Association]] (CPA) of [[Edina, Minnesota]] and [[Great River Energy|United Power Association]] (UPA) of [[Elk River (Minnesota)|Elk River, Minnesota]]. CPA and UPA were Minnesota electrical generation and transmission associations comprised of a combined total of 34 retail [[Utility cooperative|electrical co-ops]].
<ref>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=3, 10}}</ref><ref name="nationm"/> Retail electrical co-ops developed following the establishment of the [[Rural Utilities Service|Rural Electrification Administration]] in 1935 and the [[Rural Electrification Act]] in 1936.<ref name=change>{{cite book |last=Clark Jr. |first=Clifford |title=[[Minnesota in a Century of Change: The State and its People since 1900]] |publisher=Minnesota Historical Society Press |year=1989 |page=135 |isbn=}}</ref>  The REA began to distribute loans to groups involved in increasing access to electricity in the rural United States. Retail electrical co-ops formed in order to be eligible for the REA's distribution loans.<ref name=change /> Co-ops often combined in federations to purchase power from private utilities or federal agencies. Occasionally these co-op associations built their own [[Power station|generating stations]].<ref name=Minn>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=10}}</ref>

===Motivation behind the CU Project===
Several factors led UPA and CPA to undertake the CU Project. UPA and CPA traditionally purchased most of their power from the [[United States Bureau of Reclamation|Bureau of Reclamation's]] [[Garrison Dam]] on the Missouri River in North Dakota.<ref name=oralhistory86>{{cite journal |last1=Fogerty |first1=James E. |year=1985 |title=Oral History and Environmental Controversy: The Minnesota Powerline Project |journal=The Oral History Review |volume=13 |pages=86}}</ref> UPA and CPA wanted to curtail their purchase of power to avoid the long term contract commitments. They desired to increase their "control over their energy supplies and costs".<ref name=oralhistory86 /> UPA and CPA predicted that they would not be able to meet the demand of retail co-op members for their electricity. As a result of the [[1973 oil crisis|oil crisis]] of the 1970s, oil prices more than doubled from 1973 to 1978. UPA and CPA believed that consumers would switch to electricity as a source of power to avoid high oil prices.<ref name=secondguess>{{cite news |title=State Powerline Still Generating Concerns and Second-guesses |author= |first=Pat |last=Doyle |authorlink= |author2= |author3= |author4= |author5= |author6= |author7= |url= |format= |agency= |newspaper=Minneapolis Star Tribune |publisher= |location= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |pmid= |pmd= |bibcode= |doi= |id= |date=November 13, 1988 |page=01A |pages= |accessdate= |language= |trans_title= |quote= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |ref= }}</ref> Demand for the electricity provided by UPA and CPA was already growing and UPA and CPA predicted that this growth would continue at the same rate.<ref>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=98}}</ref> A 1972 study of the CU Project's feasibility predicted that UPA and CPA would face a "projected power generation deficit of 665 megawatts by 1978".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fogerty |first1=James E. |year=1985 |title=Oral History and Environmental Controversy: The Minnesota Powerline Project |journal=The Oral History Review |volume=13 |pages=79}}</ref> As well, UPA and CPA needed the CU Project to meet their agreements with the [[Midwest Reliability Organization|Mid-continent Area Power Pool]] (MAPP), an association of twenty-eight utilities serving seven states in the Midwest.<ref name=nationm>{{cite journal |last1=McKeon |first1=Mark |last2= |first2= |date=October 30, 1976 |title=High Tension on the Prairie |journal=The Nation |volume= |pages=436 |url= |doi= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=6}}</ref> In order to join MAPP, UPA and CPA had to sign an agreement that obligated them to "power pool" or maintain a 15% surplus of power for sale to the other members of MAPP.<ref>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=11, 7}}</ref><ref name=nationm />

===The CU Project and the REA===
In 1972, UPA and CPA approached REA about the possibility of building a new generating station.<ref name="wellstone13"/> The REA favored a lignite coal generator in North Dakota over a Minnesota plant using [[Montana]] coal shipped by train.<ref name=wellstone13 /> The REA had financed other [[lignite]] coal generators in North Dakota, three of which were among the ten most economical plants in the country in the early 1970s.<ref name=wellstone13 />
The REA agreed to finance the construction through low-interest loans.<ref name=wellstone3>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=3}}</ref> At the time of construction, the CU project was the largest and most expensive single project in the history of the REA.<ref name=wellstone3 /><ref name=wellstone28>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=28}}</ref> When the project was announced, there was only one other comparable high voltage powerline in the United States: the Bonneville Power Administration's [[Pacific DC Intertie|Pacific Intertie]] that runs from Oregon to Los Angeles.<ref name=wellstone3 /><ref name=wellstone16>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=16}}</ref>

==The CU Project==
===Components===
The CU Project consists of three parts: the Falkirk Mine, the Coal Creek Generating Station, and the [[CU (Powerline)|CU Powerline]].<ref name=wellstone15>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=15}}</ref> A subsidiary of [[North American Coal Corporation]] runs the Falkirk Mine, a lignite coal strip mine in North Dakota that covers over twenty-five square miles and uses two of the biggest [[dragline excavator]]s  ever assembled.<ref name=wellstone15 /> The lignite uncovered by the draglines travels by conveyor belt to [[Coal Creek Station]], the largest lignite-fired plant in North Dakota.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coal_Creek_Station |title=Coal Creek Station |first= |last= |author= |authorlink= |coauthors= |date= |work= |publisher= |location= |page= |pages= |language= |trans_title= |format= |doi= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |accessdate=November 23, 2009 |quote= |ref= |separator= |postscript= }}</ref><ref name=wellstone15 /> The Coal Creek Station produces AC current which is converted into DC current at a conversion station.<ref name=wellstone15 /> This DC current is transmitted from Coal Creek Station in North Dakota  430 miles to a station near [[Delano, Minnesota]] where it is converted back into AC current. The powerline crosses 9 western and central Minnesota counties and includes a total of 659 towers placed at one-quarter mile intervals on the property of 476 landowners: primarily corn, wheat, soybean, and sugar beet farms.<ref name=fogerty80>{{cite journal |last1=Fogerty |first1=James E. |year=1985 |title=Oral History and Environmental Controversy: The Minnesota Powerline Project |journal=The Oral History Review |volume=13 |pages=80}}</ref>

===Arguments against the CU Project===
The first opponents to the CU Project were farmers who found out that the powerline would be built on their land. Farmers were upset with the way that the powerline route was initially conceived. In 1973 UPA and CPA hired a consulting firm which used a numbering system to assess the value of the land between North Dakota and Minnesota. They assigned high numbers (more value) to airports, highways, and wildlife areas but zero to agricultural land.<ref name=wellstone17>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=17}}</ref> The line would cross diagonally across farms, which farmers believed would disrupt irrigation and aerial spraying and seeding, limit future land use, and reduce the value of the land.<ref name="wellstone28"/><ref name=wellstone7>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=7}}</ref> Farmers believed that their way of life was being disrupted to "supply mainly urban population centers" with power.<ref name=wellstone37>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=37}}</ref> UPA and CPA customers did not like the fact that their electricity bills would be increased in order to pay off the loans the REA and other creditors had granted UPA and CPA to finance the project.<ref name=wellstone18>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=18}}</ref> Opponents believed that CPA and UPA "[[Demand forecasting|demand forecasts]] might be self-serving" and that alternatives to building the line such as [[Energy conservation|conservation]] were not seriously considered.<ref name=wellstone101>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=101}}</ref><ref name=wellstone112>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=112}}</ref> Farmers worried that the [[Electromagnetic radiation and health|effects of direct electrical current]] on livestock and humans had not been adequately explored.<ref name=health>{{cite web |url=http://news.minnesota.publicradio.org/features/200212/08_losurem_powerline6/ |title=The towers are falling |first=Mary |last=Losure |author= |authorlink= |coauthors= |date= |work= |publisher=Minnesota Public Radio |location= |page= |pages= |language= |trans_title= |format= |doi= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |accessdate=November 23, 2009 |quote= |ref= |separator= |postscript= }}</ref>

