|30 = '''September 9, 1980''': CPA and UPA requested that the REA assume ownership of the powerline <ref name=wellstone287>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=287}}</ref>
}}

Following the EQC decision to issue a construction permit to CPA and UPA and several years of legal battles and public hearings, farmers were "no longer in a mood to work within the system".<ref name=wellstone135>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=135}}</ref> On June 8, 1976 a farmer smashed a surveying tripod with his tractor and rammed a pickup truck belonging to the survey crew.<ref name=wellstone136>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=136}}</ref> This was the first act of illegal protest against the powerline.

Following the events of June 8, farmers notified each other by [[Citizens' band radio|CB radio]] regarding surveying activities and turned out in groups to block the surveyors' work.<ref name=wellstone137>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=137}}</ref> As the protests grew in momentum, local radio stations carried news of when and where protesters would gather.<ref name=wellstone145>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=145}}</ref> The Lowry town hall became the headquarters where protesters, some having traveled from surrounding counties, would gather every morning to make plans.<ref name=wellstone186>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=186}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Minnesota Farmers Harass Surveyors for Power Lines |author= |first= |last= |authorlink= |author2= |author3= |author4= |author5= |author6= |author7= |url= |format= |agency= |newspaper=The New York Times |publisher= |location= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |pmid= |pmd= |bibcode= |doi= |id= |date=January 25, 1978 |page= |pages=A12 |accessdate= |language= |trans_title= |quote= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |ref= }}</ref> The survey crews began to be accompanied by law enforcement.

Farmers used a variety of tactics to thwart surveying on their property. They raised signs on poles to block the view of the surveyors.<ref name=wellstone>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=142}}</ref> When a protester was hauled away for blocking the surveyor's line of sight, another protester would take the original protester's place.<ref name=wellstone146>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=146}}</ref> Farmers ran chainsaws to make it difficult for surveyors to hear and communicate. On one instance, farmers were granted permission by their town board to repair a road leading to a survey site. When survey crews arrived, farmers had put up roadblocks and were in the process of digging a hole in the road.<ref name=wellstone145 /> Farmers used their tractors to pile boulders around the tower base holes preventing concrete from being poured. One farmer parked his truck with the key broken off in the ignition to block cement mixers. Another farmer "drove upwind of a utility crew then switched on his manure spreader". Survey stakes would vanish overnight.<ref name=wellstone179>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=179}}</ref>

===Mobilization of state troopers===
On January 4, 1978, a hundred farmers chased powerline crews from three different sites and "scuffled" with state troopers.<ref name=wellstone201>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=201}}</ref> Protesters dismantled parts of a tower in full view of the troopers.<ref name=LA>{{cite news |title=Troopers Guard Minnesota Power Crews |author= |first= |last= |authorlink= |author2= |author3= |author4= |author5= |author6= |author7= |url= |format= |agency= |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |publisher= |location= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |pmid= |pmd= |bibcode= |doi= |id= |date=January 8, 1978 |page= |pages=A6 |accessdate= |language= |trans_title= |quote= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |ref= }}</ref> The following Friday, [[Rudy Perpich|Governor Perpich]] ordered what was, at the time, the largest mobilization of state troopers in Minnesota history.<ref name=LA /> National and international news reporters began arriving in Lowry to cover the protest.<ref name=Minnesota1 /><ref name="wellstone202"/> On January 9, 200 protesters marched across a survey site to hand each trooper a plastic carnation. Protesters also offered troopers coffee and cookies.<ref name=peaceful>{{cite news |title=A Power Line Protest is Peaceful |author= |first= |last= |authorlink= |author2= |author3= |author4= |author5= |author6= |author7= |url= |format= |agency= |newspaper=The New York Times |publisher= |location= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |pmid= |pmd= |bibcode= |doi= |id= |date=January 10, 1978 |page=30 |pages= |accessdate= |language= |trans_title= |quote= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |ref= }}</ref><ref name=wellstone202 /> The protest numbers continued to grow throughout January 1978. Thousands of farmers rallied in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]]. In one community, school was let out so teachers and students could join the rally.<ref name=wellstone211>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=211}}</ref>

===The "Battle of Stearns County"===
On February 15, 1978, farmers sprayed troopers with anhydrous ammonia, a fertilizer that can cause serious chemical burns.<ref name=Minnesota1 /><ref name=wellstone216>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=216}}</ref> Media reaction to this act was negative and protesters became divided over tactics.<ref name=wellstone218>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=218}}</ref> Protesters began making greater use of nonviolent resistance. Protesters covered themselves in pig manure and asked the police to arrest them.<ref name=wellstone219>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=219}}</ref>

==="March for Justice"===
On March 5, 1978 over eight thousand people marched from [[Lowry, Minnesota|Lowry]] to [[Glenwood, Minnesota|Glenwood]] in below freezing temperatures to protest the CU Project. Marchers followed a tractor draped with an American flag that carried a coffin labeled "Justice" and a figure labeled "Corporate Giant".<ref name="wellstone220"/>

==="Bolt Weevils"===
Beginning in August 1978, a group that called themselves the "Bolt Weevils" began to sabotage power line towers and shoot out electrical insulators.<ref name="wellstone273"/><ref name=wellstone277>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=277}}</ref> The General Assembly to Stop the Powerline (GASP) put out a regular newsletter called Hold That Line. One issue commented on the acts of the Bolt Weevils: "It is a mistake  to label these as acts of vandalism. Vandalism means 'ignorant destruction of property,' and it would be a big misunderstanding to think that these acts are creatures of ignorance".<ref name=wellstone275>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=275}}</ref> The electrical co-ops hired outside security officers that used helicopters and vehicles to patrol the line.<ref name=wellstone278>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=278}}</ref> UPA and CPA launched a public relations campaign to communicate to customers that vandalism would lead to electric bill increases.<ref name=wellstone281>{{cite book |last=Wellstone |first=Paul |coauthors=Barry M. Casper |title=[[Powerline: The First Battle of America<U+2019>s Energy War]] |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1981 |isbn=0-8166-4384-9 |page=281}}</ref> On August 1, 1979 the CU powerline went into commercial operation. On September 9, 1980, the REA took ownership of the line, in part so that attacks on the line would become federal offenses.<ref name="wellstone287"/> In the end, Bolt Weevils tore down 14 power line towers and shot out nearly 10,000 electrical insulators.<ref name=wellstonen />

==Consequences==
In the end, protesters were unsuccessful in blocking construction of the powerline. The fight had the unintended consequence of higher payments to farmers whose land was taken for the powerline.<ref name=health />
From 1976 to 1978, 120 people were arrested in connection with the protest. 4 people were convicted of criminal counts and 1 was convicted of felony charges.<ref name="wellstone286"/>

Soon after the powerline entered commercial operation, UPA and CPA saw a dropoff in demand for electricity. UPA and CPA ended up selling this surplus electricity to other utilities.<ref name=secondguess /> Eventually, consumer demand increased. Since 1980, consumer demand for electricity in Minnesota has doubled. In the late 2000s, [[Xcel Energy|Xcel Energy, Inc.]] and 10 other utility companies announced plans to build a new high-voltage transmission line.<ref name=charged>{{cite news |title=A Less-Charged Debate |author= |first=Mike |last=Meyers |authorlink= |author2= |author3= |author4= |author5= |author6= |author7= |url= |format= |agency= |newspaper=Minneapolis Star Tribune |publisher= |location= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |pmid= |pmd= |bibcode= |doi= |id= |date=January 14, 2007 |page=1D |pages= |accessdate= |language= |trans_title= |quote= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |ref= }}</ref>

A report detailing health concerns about the CU powerline was cited by a judge as a reason to block powerline construction in Texas.<ref name=secondguess />

In the mid-2000s, a new group calling itself the "Bolt Weevils" emerged in Minnesota. The group vandalized [[Syngenta|Novartis]]/Northrup-King<U+2019>s Seed research facility and trampled 50 rows of research corn adjacent to [[Pioneer Hi-Bred]]<U+2019>s seed research facility.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foodsafety.ksu.edu/en/news-details.php?a=3&c=29&sc=220&id=38543 |title=BOLT WEEVILS COMMUNIQUE |first= |last= |author=International Food Safety Network |authorlink= |coauthors= |date=January 1, 2005 |work= |publisher= |location= |page= |pages= |language= |trans_title= |format= |doi= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |accessdate=November 24, 2009 |quote= |ref= |separator= |postscript= }}</ref>

==Organizations formed to fight the power line==
*Counties United for a Rural Environment (CURE): the first umbrella organization for groups fighting the powerline
*Families are Concerned Too (FACT): Pope County anti-powerline group
*General Assembly to Stop the Powerline (GASP): umbrella organization formed in January 1978, based in Lowry, Minnesota
*Keep Towers Out (KTO): Stearns County anti-powerline group
*No Powerline (NPL): Grant County anti-powerline group
*Preserve Grant County (PGC): Grant County anti-powerline group
*Save Our Countryside (SOC): Douglas County anti-powerline group
*Towers Out of Pope Association (TOOPA): Pope County anti-powerline group
*Families Are Concerned Too

==Inspired art==
*"Minnesota Line" song by Nancy Abrams
*"We Don't Want No Powerlines Around Here" song by Russell Packard
*"The Towers Are Falling" song by the Unity Theatre, Minneapolis
*"Powerline Blues" song by Charlie Broten
*"OHMS" made for television movie shown on [[CBS]] during January 1980

